SIMPLE: loyal
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Loyal
<hw>Loy"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>loyal</ets>,
OF. <ets>loial</ets>, <ets>leial</ets>, L. <ets>legalis</ets>, fr.
<ets>lex</ets>, <ets>legis</ets>, law. See <er>Legal</er>, and cf.
<er>Leal</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Faithful to law; upholding the lawful authority;
faithful and true to the lawful government; faithful to the prince or
sovereign to whom one is subject; unswerving in allegiance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Welcome, sir John ! But why come you in arms ? --⟦br⟧
To help King Edward in his time of storm,⟦br⟧
As every <qex>loyal</qex> subject ought to do.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>True to any person or persons to whom one owes
fidelity, especially as a wife to her husband, lovers to each other, and
friend to friend; constant; faithful to a cause or a
principle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your true and <qex>loyal</qex> wife.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unhappy both, but <qex>loyal</qex>their loves.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loyalist</ent>⟦br⟧
